Data analysis

Table

fse

We fitted a linear mixed model (estimated using REML and nloptwrap optimizer) to predict fse with age, group and time_point (formula: fse ~ 1 + age + group + time_point + group * time_point). The model included login_id as random effect (formula: ~1 | login_id). The model’s total explanatory power is substantial (conditional R2 = 0.70) and the part related to the fixed effects alone (marginal R2) is of 0.11. The model’s intercept, corresponding to age = 0, group = control and time_point = 1st , is at 14.17 (S.E. = 2.04, p < .001, 95% CI [10.17, 18.18]). Within this model:

  • The effect of age is statistically significant and positive (beta = 0.08, S.E. = 0.04, p = 0.040, 95% CI [3.37e-03, 0.15]; Std. beta = 0.27, 95% CI [0.01, 0.53])
  • The effect of group [treatment] is statistically non-significant and negative (beta = -0.52, S.E. = 1.04, p = 0.614, 95% CI [-2.56, 1.51]; Std. beta = -0.13, 95% CI [-0.64, 0.38])
  • The effect of time point [2nd] is statistically non-significant and negative (beta = -0.69, S.E. = 0.81, p = 0.395, 95% CI [-2.27, 0.90]; Std. beta = -0.17, 95% CI [-0.57, 0.22])
  • The interaction effect of time point [2nd] on group [treatment] is statistically significant and positive (beta = 3.46, S.E. = 1.20, p = 0.004, 95% CI [1.10, 5.82]; Std. beta = 0.86, 95% CI [0.27, 1.45])

Standardized parameters were obtained by fitting the model on a standardized version of the dataset. 95% Confidence Intervals (CIs) and p-values were computed using a Wald normal distribution approximation.
